2️⃣ UNSUPERVISED LEARNING
Definition

In Unsupervised Learning, there are no labels.

Dataset looks like:

Age	Salary	Purchases
25	40k	medium
50	120k	high
22	30k	low

But we don't know the categories.

The machine must discover patterns itself.

Main Tasks in Unsupervised Learning

Two major tasks exist.

1️⃣ Clustering

Grouping similar data points.

Example:

Customer data.

ML groups customers like:

Group 1 → High spenders
Group 2 → Medium spenders
Group 3 → Low spenders

Algorithm used:

👉 K-Means Clustering

Real Example

E-commerce companies cluster customers to:

target ads
recommend products
optimize marketing
2️⃣ Dimensionality Reduction

Sometimes datasets have too many features.

Example:

An image dataset might have:

1000 features

Many features are unnecessary.

Dimensionality reduction compresses the data while keeping important information.

Algorithm:

👉 Principal Component Analysis

Why this is important

It helps with:

faster training
visualization
removing noise
🔷 Real World Uses of Unsupervised Learning
Customer Segmentation

Companies divide customers into groups.

Example:

luxury buyers
budget buyers
occasional buyers
Recommendation Systems

ML identifies similar user behavior.

Example:

If users who bought Laptop also bought Mouse, the system recommends mouse.

Used by:

Amazon
YouTube
Spotify
3️⃣ SEMI-SUPERVISED LEARNING

Sometimes labeled data is very expensive.

Example:

Medical images.

Doctors must label each image.

This is time consuming.

So dataset may look like:

100 labeled images
10,000 unlabeled images

Semi-supervised learning uses:

small labeled data
+
large unlabeled data

The model first learns from labeled data, then improves using unlabeled data.

Real Example

Image recognition datasets.

Only few images are labeled.

ML models use both types.

4️⃣ REINFORCEMENT LEARNING

This type is inspired by how humans learn by reward and punishment.

Core Idea

There is:

Agent → makes decision
Environment → responds
Reward → feedback

Example:

Dog training.

Good action → reward
Bad action → punishment

The agent learns best strategy over time.

Reinforcement Learning Loop
Agent takes action
↓
Environment gives reward
↓
Agent learns from reward
↓
Agent improves decision
Real World Uses
Game AI

Used in games like:

Chess
Go

AI learns by playing millions of games.

Robotics

Robots learn:

walking
grabbing objects
navigation
Self Driving Cars

Cars learn:

lane detection
braking
turning

Companies like:

Tesla
Waymo

use these systems.

